# PROJECT

## SDD Workflow

This project follows spec-driven development. The skill chain, in order, is:

`brainstorming` тЖТ `prd-writer` тЖТ `spec-writer` тЖТ `clarify` тЖТ `plan-writer` тЖТ `tasks-writer` тЖТ `analyze` тЖТ `implement-and-evaluate` тЖТ `review-and-simplify` тЖТ `finishing-a-development-branch`

`implement-and-evaluate` is the execution loop. It runs each task in one of two modes, chosen once from the shape of `tasks.md`/`plan.md` (see its `## Mode Selection` and `docs/design-notes/execution-mode-routing.md`): **inline** тАФ invoking `implement-feature` as a child skill on the session model (short or tightly-coupled features) тАФ or **dispatch** тАФ delegating to `subagent-driven-development` for fresh per-task implementer subagents with cost-aware model routing (3+ independent tasks). `implement-feature` is therefore a child of `implement-and-evaluate`, not a sibling step run before it.

When processing review feedback (from the user, a human reviewer, or the `review-and-simplify` lenses), follow `receiving-code-review`: verify before implementing, push back with technical reasoning when a suggestion is wrong, never performative agreement. After the approved commit(s), `finishing-a-development-branch` presents the integrate options (merge / PR / keep / discard) and handles worktree cleanup.

`brainstorming` is the entry point for any non-trivial feature, refactor, or bug fix. DO NOT write code before a spec and plan both carry `status: approved` in their frontmatter. The phase-gate hook (`core/claude/hooks/phase-gate.mjs`) enforces this mechanically тАФ it blocks Edit/Write on code files until both `spec.md` and `plan.md` for the active feature are approved. Work around the gate by getting approval, never by disabling or bypassing it.

`review-and-simplify` is a MANDATORY pre-commit step: it runs the review lenses (`code-review` + `security-review`) in parallel and a behavior-preserving `simplify` pass before any commit is proposed тАФ a commit must never be proposed without it.

**TDD is a REQUIRED step.** All implementation (`implement-feature` and any dispatched implementer subagent) MUST follow the `test-driven-development` skill: no production code without a failing test first (Iron Law), red тЖТ green тЖТ refactor per behavior. Test BEHAVIOR тАФ observable inputs/outputs/effects тАФ NOT implementation details, and NEVER assert on mocks. A test that breaks on a behavior-preserving refactor is testing implementation; rewrite it. This is not optional; "test-after" does not satisfy it.

## Commits

Accumulate changes and commit at the END of a feature or milestone тАФ NOT after every task, step, or TDD cycle. When dispatching subagents, instruct them to implement/test/report only; they NEVER commit. Once tests are green and quality gates pass, propose the commit message(s) and wait for explicit approval before running `git commit`.

## Quality Gates

Run `.specify/gates/run-gates.sh` to check the project. DO NOT invent your own ad-hoc gates (no hand-rolled lint/test invocations outside what the script already runs). The precommit-gate hook (`core/claude/hooks/precommit-gate.mjs`) runs `run-gates.sh` automatically before any `git commit` and blocks the commit if gates fail.

The runner detects and runs the project **build** stack-independently тАФ `npm run build`, `make build`, `go build ./...`, `cargo build`, Maven, Gradle, or .NET, whichever matches. So "does it still build?" is verified at the end of every feature: `implement-and-evaluate`'s final `fix-runner` pass runs the gates, and the precommit-gate hook re-runs them before commit тАФ a feature with a broken build cannot be committed. A project with no compile step (interpreted, no build) matches nothing and the build gate is correctly a no-op.

The runner includes **doc-layer conformance gates** (zero-dep node, always run):
- `audit-structure` тАФ skills carry `name`/`description` frontmatter, every `specs/NNNN-*/` has `spec.md`, no broken relative links.
- `eval-spec-fidelity` тАФ once a feature has `tasks.md`, every `AC-N` in its `spec.md` MUST be referenced by a task (traceability); AC not yet in code/test is a warning. Tag acceptance criteria `AC-1`, `AC-2`тАж in the spec and cite the `AC-N` in the task that delivers it.
- `validate-mermaid` тАФ structural check of ` ```mermaid ` blocks.

When you knowingly diverge from an approved spec, mark the spot in code with a `SPEC_DEVIATION` comment explaining why; `eval-spec-fidelity` counts open deviations so they are not forgotten.

## Code style

- Functions: 4-20 lines. Files: under 400 lines.
- Single responsibility per function/module.
- Specific names тАФ avoid generic placeholders like `data`, `handler`, `Manager`.
- Explicit types everywhere; no `any`.

## Security

Authorization and permission checks on fields like `source`, `role`, `type`, `origin`, `createdVia`, or `userGroup` MUST allow-list the permitted value тАФ never deny-list the known-bad value. New/unexpected values must be blocked by default. Prefer an enum over a string literal for the allowed set.

```ts
// wrong тАФ blacklist (new values pass through silently)
if (entity.sourceApp === 'admin') throw new ForbiddenException();

// right тАФ whitelist (new values are blocked by default)
if (entity.sourceApp !== 'expected-source') throw new ForbiddenException();
```

## Comments

Comment WHY, not WHAT тАФ the code already says what it does. Docstrings should state intent plus a short example. Reference the relevant issue or commit SHA when a comment explains a workaround or a non-obvious historical decision.

## Structure

Keep modules small and focused on one concern. Use predictable, conventional paths so files can be found without searching.

When designing a feature's structure (during `plan-writer`), use the `architecture` skill тАФ agnostic guides for Clean Architecture, SOLID, testing strategy, and DDD tactical тАФ and fill `.specify/templates/architecture-template.md`. The constitution's `## Princ├нpios de arquitetura` (dependency rule, pure domain, aggregate boundary, test behavior) are non-negotiable. Mechanical enforcement of the dependency rule is per-language and ships in a pack, not in core.

Before designing structure, ground the plan in the real tree with the `codebase-map` skill: it maps the repo ONCE into `docs/codebase-map.md` (a token-lean, depth-limited structural map) so `plan-writer`, `analyze`, and `implement-feature` reuse it instead of re-exploring each phase. Generate/refresh it at feature start when the repo is non-trivial or the map has drifted; skip on small repos.

## Continuity & decisions

`docs/STATE.md` is the **volatile** work memory тАФ where we stopped, the next concrete step, blockers. It is injected into context at SessionStart. Use the `handoff` skill to write it when pausing and to recompose context when resuming. Keep it short and actionable.

Durable architecture decisions go in `docs/architecture/adr/NNNN-*.md` (use `_template.md`), not in STATE. ADRs are append-only: to change a decision, write a new ADR that supersedes the old one. Rule of thumb: hard-to-reverse decision тЖТ ADR; current work state тЖТ STATE.

### Open Knowledge Format index

Any `.md` under `docs/`, `specs/`, or `.specify/memory/` that carries a `type:` key in its frontmatter is indexed at SessionStart by the `okf-index` hook (`core/claude/hooks/okf-index.mjs`) and injected as a compact map (concept name, type, path, `[[links]]`) тАФ so documented schemas, metrics, APIs, and decisions are in context from turn one with zero tool calls. To register a concept, give the doc `type:` (e.g. `table`, `metric`, `api`, `service`) and optionally `name:`/`title:` frontmatter, and cross-reference related concepts with `[[wiki-links]]` in the body. Docs without `type:` are ignored, so the index stays signal-only; the injected map is capped at 60 concepts to bound token cost.

## Multi-client views

This Claude Code setup (`CLAUDE.md` + `.claude/`) is the **canonical source**. If the project was bootstrapped with `--agent=` / `--all`, view files for other agents (Codex `AGENTS.md` + `.agents/`, Cursor `.cursor/`, Copilot `.github/copilot-instructions.md` + `.github/prompts/`, Gemini `GEMINI.md` + `.gemini/`, Windsurf `.windsurf/`) are **generated, advisory, and read-only** тАФ they carry the instructions and skills but NOT the mechanical enforcement (gates/hooks are Claude-Code-only). Never hand-edit a view; change the canonical source and regenerate with `bootstrap.sh --force --agent=...`. The doc gates ignore generated view dirs. `.specify/clients.json` records which clients are generated.

## Logging

Use structured JSON for debug/diagnostic logging. Use plain text for user-facing output.
